10:16.876 --> 10:25.948
power? SECRETARY KERRY, Let me begin with 
President Carter's administration. From the

10:35.375 --> 10:42.449
perspective of the nuclear industry, President 
Carter's administration was essentially a

10:35.375 --> 10:42.449
disaster.

10:45.334 --> 10:57.197
And let me hasten to note that what I'm going to say 
now is strictly a personal opinion, but in my

10:45.334 --> 10:57.197
estimation,

10:57.970 --> 11:26.745
the stands, if you will, that the Carter 
administration took with regards to nuclear

10:57.970 --> 11:26.745
power were effectively based on what

10:57.970 --> 11:26.745
is almost a total lack of understanding, in my 
estimation, with regards to the purpose and

10:57.970 --> 11:26.745
function hazards or lacks of hazards with regards 
to nuclear power. President Carter, I think,

11:27.282 --> 11:37.320
started out his administration on the wrong foot 
with regards to the nuclear industry. I think his,

11:39.644 --> 11:46.756
where he really shot himself in the foot was when he 
contended that he was a nuclear engineer. He was

11:47.838 --> 11:50.723
taken to task on that point very rapidly. I think 
his closest association with things nuclear was

11:52.190 --> 12:11.964
the fact that he had spent some few weeks or a month 
or whatever on a nuclear submarine and in his

11:52.190 --> 12:11.964
estimation that was sufficient to allow him to 
