19:29.536 --> 19:41.183
In light of the current research and the current 
information available, what do you see as the

19:29.536 --> 19:41.183
state of the art in technology in specific regard 
to plutonium technology?

19:44.335 --> 19:50.945
That question covers a very, very wide range of 
activities.

19:52.427 --> 20:04.004
I think that, well, let me say that plutonium is a 
material that is, from a scientific point of view,

19:52.427 --> 20:04.004
is very fascinating to work with. It has a very 
complex chemistry. It has an extremely complex

20:06.828 --> 20:09.111
metallurgy. I think there is obviously a great 
deal of work that is being done and needs to be done

20:09.631 --> 20:23.876
in the future from a purely scientific point of 
view. I think that there are a number of

20:24.737 --> 20:33.613
developments that are in the offing. for 
instance, with regards to the metallurgy of

20:34.488 --> 20:47.384
plutonium that are of potential great value to the 
weapons programs in the country. I think there's a

20:48.085 --> 20:54.413
great deal of very interesting work that is being 
done. And I think that certainly significant

20:54.453 --> 21:04.005
developments relative to the manufacture of 
plutonium and the processing of plutonium in one

21:04.255 --> 21:18.856
light or another that will be a substantial 
advantage with regards to the weapons industry.

21:20.759 --> 21:33.317
In other areas, for instance, reactor fuels, 
there's a great deal of work to be done there.

21:33.736 --> 21:49.620
The principal place where plutonium is used in the 
reactor industry is with regards to the

21:33.736 --> 21:49.620
development and operation of, at the present 
time, liquid metal fast breeder reactors. That is

21:49.720 --> 21:56.710
the primary place where plutonium would be used in 
the reactor industry. There's a great deal to be

21:59.094 --> 22:02.038
done there. Frankly, I think that the LMFBR

22:02.525 --> 22:17.359
industry in the United States is operating at a 
severe disadvantage. Well, and by disadvantage I

22:18.840 --> 22:31.452
mean that the LMFBR development in this country 
has been very heavily well,

22:31.837 --> 22:44.774
has been held back to a very major extent because of 
the regulatory problems that I mentioned a moment

22:31.837 --> 22:44.774
ago.

22:49.661 --> 23:00.696
Well, the development of LMFBRs in this country is 
very substantially behind that in many of the

22:49.661 --> 23:00.696
other major countries around the world. The 
French, for instance, are really at the forefront

23:01.283 --> 23:08.452
of development. The Germans are working. The 
British have a substantial amount going that is

23:11.475 --> 23:21.247
significantly in advance of what we're doing now. 
Unfortunately, it's really kind of interesting

23:22.349 --> 23:30.919
with the fact that because of the anti-nuclear 
movements, and the various regulatory problems

23:31.152 --> 23:59.404
that the LMFBR people have run into in this country 
that led to the LMFBR being effectively

23:31.152 --> 23:59.404
downplayed or downgraded has had an interesting 
reflection in some of the European countries that

23:31.152 --> 23:59.404
were vigorously moving toward the development of 
an LMFBR. we began to back up and for some reason

23:59.941 --> 24:29.475
they started backing up too and it's almost as 
though it was a the system became unstable to a

23:59.941 --> 24:29.475
certain extent and much of the the pressure or 
impetus if you will to the development of LMFBRs

23:59.941 --> 24:29.475
has begun to to lose its momentum And that I 
personally feel

24:30.147 --> 24:40.740
is going to be a very major problem not very many 
years into the future. I can see very major

24:41.541 --> 24:52.575
difficulties on the horizon with regards to the 
availability of power. And the LMFBR was

24:52.595 --> 24:57.741
originally intended to help close that gap. But 
it's beginning to appear to me that that gap is not

25:02.725 --> 25:11.613
only not being closed, we're losing ground on it. 
And there may be, there may come a time when the

25:12.014 --> 25:26.428
power situation in the world will make us all rue 
the day that the LNFBR was What are the problems

25:27.488 --> 25:38.619
with the LMFBR that inspire the over-regulation 
or the dissent against that program? I think the

25:39.580 --> 25:45.525
dissent is primarily based on concerns with 
safety. There are several scenarios, many of

25:46.927 --> 25:56.736
which in my estimation are simply not credible. 
that lead some to feel that the LMFBR is simply not

25:57.155 --> 26:11.719
safe to have

25:57.155 --> 26:11.719
in the country. They envision LMFBRs, or reactors 
in general, as effectively being a a bomb sitting

26:21.725 --> 26:26.770
there waiting to explode, and that simply is not 
the case. They cannot explode in that way. I must

26:32.096 --> 26:41.245
hasten to add that reactors are not without risk. 
There are things that can happen that can cause

26:41.325 --> 26:44.969
problems. However, I think many of the problems 
that are effectively suggested as being probable

26:49.636 --> 27:10.958
are really extremely unlikely situations and I 
think they're just not at all, they're so unlikely

26:49.636 --> 27:10.958
that they really in my estimation should be of no 
major concern. One of the other things that is

27:12.400 --> 27:19.187
leading to concern about the LMFBR is the fact that 
many people, and I'm sure they are expert in their

27:19.758 --> 27:33.418
area, are suggesting that uranium reserves in 
this country are such that the LMFBR truly is not

27:19.758 --> 27:33.418
needed. And by that I mean that you can operate 
power reactors as

27:46.960 --> 27:50.304
as the light water reactors are operated now. You 
simply burn the uranium and throw away the fission

27:50.384 --> 27:55.630
products and that's that. And you don't have any 
mechanism for continuing to grow new fissile

27:56.370 --> 28:04.940
material. That is the virtue of the breeder. It 
effectively manufactures more fuel than it

28:07.863 --> 28:10.946
burns. That is fine as long as you have of 
sufficient uranium to keep the system operating

28:15.665 --> 28:20.735
effectively ad infinitum. I, frankly, am not very 
comfortable with that new plan. I'm afraid we're

28:25.485 --> 28:34.483
going to need it over here, and it may be too late 
once it's really recognized as being needed.

28:37.535 --> 28:54.137
Dr. Green, in conclusion, do you feel that since 
its conception that the nuclear industry or the

28:37.535 --> 28:54.137
field of nuclear research has advanced, and if so, 
do you believe that it will continue to be a viable

28:37.535 --> 28:54.137
source or an energy program in the future? Well, I 
think from a technological point of view, over the

28:55.438 --> 29:05.331
few years that the industry has been in existence, 
technologically there have been tremendous

28:55.438 --> 29:05.331
advances. Unfortunately, it almost appears 
like, in a political sense, the industry has been

29:05.648 --> 29:16.058
marching backwards. That is to say that its 
acceptance by the man on the street has degraded

29:16.639 --> 29:35.217
very dramatically and in a very discouraging way, 
as far as I'm concerned. It's really too bad, I

29:35.922 --> 29:43.852
think, that people have developed such a 
mistrust. And I think that, as I said earlier, I

29:44.814 --> 29:56.309
think a great deal of that mistrust is born of fear, 
and most of the fear is born in ignorance. And I wish

29:56.870 --> 29:59.533
we could turn that around.

